The calm before the storm....

In less than an hour, our very "WHY" will walk through these front doors or join their classroom through the power of the internet. A lot preparation, sweat, tears and prayers have gone into this very moment. While I can't guarantee that the day will go perfect, what I can assure you is that these students will be LOVED perfectly... OUR MISSION IS GREATER THAN ANY OBSTACLE... WE ARE EASTBROOK NORTH....WE'VE GOT THIS!

Boys Basketball Camp is next week July 22-26 for students entering K-8th grade! Don‚Äôt worry if you forgot to sign up, just come out Monday morning and you can register just before the time of your appropriate age level camp (see flyer for details).

All campers will receive a free camp T-shirt, a new basketball, individualized instruction from the staff/varsity players, and the opportunity to compete in various skills competitions for prizes throughout the week!

post_text:
We kicked off our Box Tops Collection Drive today. It's Boys vs. Girls and our goal is to collect 10,000 Box Tops by February 22.

Every Box Top earns 10 cents for our school and supports awesome programs like AR, Tin Caps, Field Trips and much more. So get family, friends and even co-workers involved by asking them to clip box tops during our drive. Bring them to the school by February 22 and place in either the Boy or Girl collection box located in the commons.

Your student should have received a flyer & collection baggie to take home today. Or see the attached flyer. For a full list of participating products, visit btfe.com/participating-products.

Thank you for participating! Happy clipping!

post_text:
In light of the weather delays and possible future delays/cancellations, the Tin Caps Committee would like to share the following update: The overall deadline will still be March 8, 2019 for K-6. However the "end of the month dates for January and February" will be adjusted to better use the extra week into March for students in grades 3-6.

January points = January 8 through end of the school day on February 6
February points = February 7 through end of the school day on March 8
[This will even out to 22 days for each month--assuming we are in school on February 18. :-)]

Please note: March 1-8 will serve a dual purpose. Tests taken on these dates will also count towards the March monthly points needed for students in grades 3-6. Therefore, March points = March 1 through March 22.

The Tin Caps Committee

post_text: Thank you to Marion General Hospital for teaching us all about the importance of hand washing! On Tuesday, MGH set up an interactive hand washing demonstration for our students to learn the importance of this practice. Using a blacklight, students were able to see how well (or not well) they washed their hands. As cold and flu season continues, we hope that students will practice what they learned about keeping their hands clean and germ-free!

post_text: The cold weather has finally arrived and we have noticed that there are some children who are not bringing the proper outerwear to go out for recess. If the temperature will be below 50 degrees at recess time, we ask that your child has a warm coat to wear for recess (we encourage younger students to have a hat and gloves, as well). If your child does not bring a coat with them, teachers will use their discretion as to whether or not they allow a child go out for recess. Our main concern is our students and their comfort & well-being. If the temperature (including wind chill) is below 20 degrees, K-3rd grade students will not go out for recess. If the temperature (including wind chill) is below 15 degrees, 4-6th grade students will not go outside for recess. If snow is on the ground, students must wear winter boots to play in the snow.

IMPORTANT ALERT:

Good morning,

This message is to alert parents of an early dismissal at Eastbrook North Elementary today. Due to an extended power outage, students will be dismissed today at 1:00pm. By that time all of our students will have been served lunch and our normal bus routes will begin. Our ENE phone lines are also down so feel free to email our office staff (mbratcher@eastbrook.k12.in.us csmoot@eastbrook.k12.in.us cmckim@eastbrook.k12.in.us) or call our central office at 664-0624 to communicate a change of plans in how your student(s) should be transported home.

Please accept our apologies for any inconveniences this causes, but trust our decision was made in the best interest of your student.

Sincerely,

Mr. McKim

post_text: Who is ready for some GREAT NEWS? This is Hunter, one of our 1st graders here at ENE. Hunter has battled cancer for the past few years, and yesterday he was officially declared CANCER FREE!!! He was able to ring a special bell at Riley Hospital to mark the occasion, and was given this special medal to wear in honor of this wonderful news. We are so proud of Hunter's bravery as he has officially "beaten cancer!"
